ignty. In such circumstances, how was the Communitarisation of the policy sector ever possible? Who were the policy actors that played a role in this process? What were their motives? And why were certain actors more influential than others? This book will be of great use to all researchers and students of European integration and European public policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBooksxMarketingxGovernment policyxEuropean Union countries. 0aBooksxMarketingxGovernment policyzEuropean Union countries. 0aBroadcasting policyxEuropean Union countries. 0aBroadcasting policyzEuropean Union countries. 0aGlobalizationxEuropean Union countries. 0aGlobalizationzEuropean Union countries. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / General.2bisacsh  aCommunitarisation.  aEU intervention.  aEuropean Union.  aarts.  acultural industries.  acultural policy sector.  amember states.  anational sovereignty.  apublic policies.  atreaties.1 aLittoz-Monnet, Annabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779221140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792211423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792211/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles